Dasymetric Map Toronto: Ethnic Diversity

Fernando Calderon-Figueroa

2022-04-24

Dasymetric Map of Toronto using MODIS and Census Data

The idea here is to reproduce Dominic Roys dasymetric map for Toronto. Roys map is scaled using the Urban and built up category of most land cover classification systems. Following Dilinie Seimons tutorial, I use the BIOME-Biogeochemical Cycles (BGC) classification system.

Some background for this version: My first attempts led to a problem. Once I created a data frame from the raster, the resulting file provided 42 classes rather than 8. Additionally, the process was lengthy due to the size of Canadas land mass. I figured out that the problem was that the variable for the x axis was not properly read from the raster into a data frame. I fixed the issue in this version by adapting the tutorials code.

The libraries used are below but the MODIS credentials are not shown. The classification used, BGC, has eight levels plus water bodies (0) and unclassified (255). See the MODISs user guide for more details.

Getting and processing the data

library(rgeoboundaries)
library(sf)
library(MODIStsp)
library(raster)
library(here)
library(tidyverse)
library(viridis)
library(tmap)
library(RColorBrewer)

# Boundaries
map_boundary = gb_adm2("Canada") %>% filter(shapeName == "Toronto")
spatial_filepath = "data/raw/toronto.shp"
st_write(map_boundary, paste0(spatial_filepath), append = FALSE)
## Deleting layer `toronto' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Writing layer `toronto' to data source 
##   `data/raw/toronto.shp' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Writing 1 features with 5 fields and geometry type Multi Polygon.
# Raster from MODIS API
MODIStsp(gui             = FALSE,
         out_folder      = "data/raw/LandCoverData",
         out_folder_mod  = "data/raw/LandCoverData",
         selprod         = "LandCover_Type_Yearly_500m (MCD12Q1)",
         bandsel         = "LC4", 
         user            = usr,
         password        = pwrd,
         start_date      = "2019.01.01", 
         end_date        = "2019.12.31", 
         verbose         = FALSE,
         spatmeth        = "file",
         spafile         = spatial_filepath,
         out_format      = "GTiff")
# Reading in the downloaded land cover raster data
BGC_raster = raster(here::here("data/raw/LandCoverData/toronto/LandCover_Type_Yearly_500m_v6/LC4/MCD12Q1_LC4_2019_001.tif"))

# Transforming data
BGC_raster = projectRaster(BGC_raster, crs = "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +no_defs")

# Masking data
BGC_raster = raster::mask(BGC_raster, as_Spatial(map_boundary))

# Converting the raster object into a dataframe and converting the BGC classification into a factor. This has been modified from the original tutorial due to a problem in reading the coordinates.

BGC_df = as.data.frame(BGC_raster, xy = TRUE, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(MCD12Q1_LC4_2019_001 = as.factor(round(MCD12Q1_LC4_2019_001)))

# renaming BGC classification levels
levels(BGC_df$MCD12Q1_LC4_2019_001) # see levels before renaming below
## [1] "0" "1" "2" "3" "4" "5" "6" "7" "8"
levels(BGC_df$MCD12Q1_LC4_2019_001) = c("Water Bodies",
                                   "Evergreen Needleleaf Vegetation",
                                   "Evergreen Broadleaf Vegetation",
                                   "Deciduous Needleleaf Vegetation",
                                   "Deciduous Broadleaf Vegetation",
                                   "Annual Broadleaf Vegetation",
                                   "Annual Grass Vegetation",
                                   "Non-Vegetated Lands",
                                   "Urban and Built-up Lands")

Land Cover Map

ggplot() + 
  geom_raster(data = BGC_df,
              aes(x = x, y = y, fill = MCD12Q1_LC4_2019_001)) +
  geom_sf(data = map_boundary, inherit.aes = FALSE, fill = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis(name = "Land Cover Type", discrete = TRUE) +
  labs(title = "Land Cover classification in Metro Toronto",
       subtitle = "01-01-2019 - 31-12-2019",
       x = "Longitude",

Local Segregation

This section draws on the 2011 Canadian Census data. I manually downloaded the data from CHASS and wrangled it in R, but the process is not shown here. In a future version, I plan to use the cancensus package.

Note that the data here include calculated segregation and diversity measures using the segregation and the diverse packages. segregation includes a local segregation measure that Ive calculated at each CMA level. The diversity measures from diverse dont include a larger scale comparison as they account for diversity within each tract. Also, I have limited the data to the five largest Census Metropolitan Areas (CMA): Toronto, Montreal, Vancouver, Ottawa-Gatineau, and Edmonton.

Reading and merging spatial data

Note that I use 2001 census geographies. The reason is that this year allows better comparisons over time.

# reading geography file (old one but works)
ct01sf = st_read("data/raw/cma5_ct01/cma5_ct01.shp") |>
  mutate(CT01 = as.numeric(CT01))
## Reading layer `cma5_ct01' from data source

# merging data
ct01seg11sf = merge(ct01sf, dat, by.x="CT01", by.y="ct01", all.x=TRUE)

Maps

Now, the maps. We want to compare a choropleth with a dasymetric map.

Local Segregation in Toronto CMA - Choropleth

pal = brewer.pal(5, "YlGnBu")
to_localseg_choro = ct01seg11sf %>% 
  filter(CMAUID == "535") %>% 
  st_transform(epgs=3857) %>% 
  tm_shape() +
  tm_borders("Gray", lwd = .25, alpha = .4) +
  tm_fill(col = "localseg_11",
          alpha = .8,
          palette = pal,
          showNA = FALSE,
          style = "kmeans") +
tm_layout(legend.title.size = 1,
          legend.text.size = 0.5,
          legend.position = c("left","top"))
to_localseg_choro

Local Segregation in Toronto CMA - Dasymetric

First, we need to process the raster.

# deleting non urban raster pixels
toronto_urban = BGC_raster
toronto_urban[!toronto_urban %in% 8] = NA

# projecting 
toronto_urban = projectRaster(toronto_urban, crs = CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"))
## Warning in projectRaster(toronto_urban, crs = CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84
## +no_defs")): input and ouput crs are the same
# tansform to xyz and sf object
toronto_urban <- as.data.frame(toronto_urban, xy = TRUE, na.rm = TRUE)
toronto_urban <- st_as_sf(toronto_urban, coords = c("x", "y"), crs = 4326)
toronto_urban <- toronto_urban %>% rename(urb = 1) %>%
  cbind(st_coordinates(toronto_urban))

# merging diversity and segregation data on spatial dots. Note that both objects are of `sf` type and projected with the same CRS.
to_localseg_points = st_join(toronto_urban, ct01seg11sf)

And now the map.

pal = brewer.pal(5, "YlGnBu")
to_localseg_dasy = ct01seg11sf %>% 
  filter(CMAUID == "535") %>% 
  st_transform(epgs=3857) %>% 
  tm_shape() +
  tm_borders("Gray", lwd = .25, alpha = .4) +
  tm_shape(to_localseg_points) +
  tm_dots(col = "localseg_11",
          palette = pal,
          showNA = FALSE,
          style = "kmeans") +
  tm_layout(legend.title.size = 1,
            legend.text.size = 0.5,
            legend.position = c("left","top"))
to_localseg_dasy

Comparison

Note that the scales are not the same in both graphs. The reason is that some tracts are not included in the k-means calculation for the dasymetric map. In a future version, I will create the breaks separatedly so that the comparison is more accurate.

tmap_arrange(to_localseg_choro, to_localseg_dasy)
